title: Photos: Spartans pull off stunning 27-23 win over Michigan
text: Photos: Spartans pull off stunning 27-23 win over Michigan Buy Photo Jalen Watts-Jackson (20) crosses the goal line to score the winning touchdown after time expired to claim the win and the Paul Bunyan trophy for Michigan State in a 27-23 over Michigan Saturday, October 17, 2015, at Michigan Stadium in Ann Arbor. Watts-Jackson recovered a muffed punt for a touchdown. Dave Wasinger/Lansing State Journal Fullscreen Buy Photo Michigan State tight end Josiah Price screams as he celebrates with teammates after a thrilling, last-second 27-23 victory over Michigan Saturday, October 17, 2015, in Ann Arbor. Dave Wasinger/Lansing State Journal MSU's Arjen Colquhoun, left, and Connor Cook, right, carry the winning Paul Bunyan trophy in Michigan Stadium after teammate Jalen Watts-Jackson ran back a Michigan fumbled or muffed punt for a touchdown and a 27-23 win Saturday 10/17/2015. Rod Sanford | Lansing State JJournal Fullscreen Buy Photo Michigan State players celebrate in the endzone after a last-second 27-23 victory over Michigan Saturday, October 17, 2015 in Ann Arbor. Dave Wasinger/Lansing State Journal Fullscreen Buy Photo Michigan State quarterback Connor Cook smiles as he hugs Quarterbacks Coach Brad Salem after the Spartans 27-23 victory over Michigan Saturday, October 17, 2015, in Michigan Stadium. Dave Wasinger/Lansing State Journal Fullscreen Buy Photo Spartans Khari Willis (27), Monty Madaris (88) and others celebrate in the endzone as Michigan players look on after Jalen Watts-Jackson scored the winning touchdown after time expired to beat the Wolverines 27-23 Saturday, October 17, 2015, at Michigan Stadium in Ann Arbor. Dave Wasinger/Lansing State Journal Fullscreen Buy Photo Jalen Watts-Jackson (20) is lifted onto a stretcher before being carted off the field after Michigan State's 27-23 win over Michigan Saturday, October 17, 2015, at Michigan Stadium in Ann Arbor. Watts-Jackson recovered a fumble for a touchdown after time expired. He was hurt in the ensuing celebration. Preliminary reports are that he broke or dislocated his hip. Pendelton made it down to the goalline before being tackled. The play was originally ruled a touchdown, but after a review he was ruled down just before the goal line.
